</td><td><img src="/images/datel.gif" width=46 height=22 border=0><img src="/images/dateblnk.gif" width=100 height=22 border=0><img src="/images/dater.gif" width=306 height=22 border=0></td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td>
	


		<td valign=top width=452><table cellspacing="4" cellpadding="6" width=100% border=0><tr><td background="/images/newsback.gif"><CENTER><H3><FONT FACE="ARIAL" color="#CB723D">Dagger</FONT></H3></CENTER>
			
		<b>Level:</b> 1<br>

		<b>Race:</b> Half-Elf<br>

		<b>Class:</b> Ranger<br>

		<b>PvP Switch:</b>  Off<br>
		
		<center><h4>History:</h4></center>  The tale of the elusive Dagger has long been a mystery until the "Shadow" himself decided to record his history. This is the tale of The Shadow Dagger.<p>One of the fiercest mercenaries of the northern lands was a skilled warrior named Darian, or as many referred to him, "Shade." He was given this name because of his stealth far surpassed that of most humans, in fact most swore he had elven blood coursing through his veins. His tales are numerous considering the length of his life, 40 years is a vast amount of time for a warrior. When he was but a young man he was part of a raid on an evil elven village, they had been assaulting one of the northern kings lands for quite some time. After the raid was complete Shade noticed one of the elves cowering in the trunk of one of the trees that held their homes. When he approached he noticed the shackles on the elf, obviously a renegade of the evil tribe. Imploring what little he knew of the elven tongue he enticed the elf from the tree and managed to slip away from the rest of the raiding party.<p>Shade hid the female elf for several months fearing her death if she was in anyway associated to the unfriendly tribe of which she was a prisoner. In this period of time they both began to learn the others language and could communicate quite well. Korri (the human pronunciation of the elf's name) revealed herself as a healer of a rival tribe that had been captured and was to be a gift to the chieftain of the evil village. While awaiting the ceremony that would surely make her a slave for eternity, she could often hear her guards bragging about their recent conquests. One tale in particular caught her attention, the tale of her home's complete destruction.<br> <br>Since Shade was a mercenary with no real home and nothing to keep him in the northern lands, and Korri had no village to go back to, they decided to venture south. The southern lands were a wild sort, but a place where the occasional elf or half-elf was not out of place. It was here that they found a home.<p>After exploring the southern lands for quite some time they discovered a heavily fortified town just west of a small mountain range. They stopped there because they had heard of the great adventure that lies in the surrounding lands. If fact town called Farreach was born of adventure. The fighters, mages, clerics, etc. developed the town as a safe haven from the Orc war parties, and the plagues of drow elves that continuously emerged from the mountains. The town had a temple, for healing, a weapon/armor shop, and many taverns and inns. There was no real law save that of each person's sword. Still the township was more interested in battling the orcs than themselves, so it was a generally quiet town. <p>The two began adventuring together and found they made a perfect team. Shade and Korri both had incredible stealth, and with Korri's healing spells backing him up Shade became that much more fearsome as a warrior. An uncanny similarity between the two was their affinity for on weapon, a dagger. Of course Shade used a long sword because of its reach, but he never used a shield, so as to use his dagger in his left hand. Korri was a marksman with a throwing dagger. She could pick off any target that threatened to flank the warrior Shade.<p>After a year as close friends and partners Korri found herself with Shade's child. The two continued adventuring with a group they had meet up with in Farreach. The Band was referred to as the Death Knights. Soon though Korri found herself unable to adventure any longer, shortly after the two had their first child, Nite. While raising their girl, Korri would often stay behind, or sometimes have Nite with the clerics at the temple. When she was old enough Nite began training at the center in the growing town. She showed a great aptitude for every skill she was shown including magic, healing, fighting, and even the art of the rogue. The only problem was she never showed much interest in any of these. She preferred use parts of each and blend them into her own style.<p>During one of their adventures when Nite was with the clerics, the group managed to jump a drow raiding party. One of the Drow (obviously the leader) was a fantastic fighter. His style was similar to Shade's, using a black long sword and an exquisite dagger. Even being a accomplished warrior Shade was no match for the experienced drow, but with the aid of Korri's magic they managed to gain an upper hand on the evil leader. After what seemed like an eternity of battle, the wounded drow made an err in his form, Shades long sword found a hole in the leaders defenses and quickly ended his life. After the battle the group searched the corpses for valuable items. When they searched the leader they found an exquisite blade with elven runes inscribed on the blade, the runes read "The Shadow Dagger." Shade decided to make this blade his own. <p>Soon after this great discovery Korri was pregnant with their second child, but the young Nite was now old enough to venture with the Death Knights. Korri often had to stay behind because of her condition, so Nite would accompany her father out into the wild lands. Shade attempted to sway Nite to the path of the warrior, but Nite preferred to fight in a light set of solid black armor, and she used 2 short swords that she was incredible quick with. Her only other weapon was a small compact crossbow she had gotten from a marksman at the town, and she tipped her arrows with a sleeping potion her mother had helped her develop. She would fully dress herself in black except for her striking blond hair, which she would sometime die black, or pull the hood of her black cloak over. At the academy she was shown some basic battle magic, which she used in conjunction with her steel duo. She also preferred to fight with surprise rather than force; her father saw the effectiveness of her style and decided it was best to let her develop the hybrid class.<p>During their adventures as father and daughter Nite began to see her father's attitudes change. He began to view the world with a very dark perspective, and he was overly vicious with his fighting. Seemingly preferring to torture a creature rather than kill it outright. Korri recognized the change as well, but as she was with child she could not be there to know for sure what was happening. Shade continued to withdraw into a darker more demented world. Korri had decided to force him to go to the temple because she was sure he had acquired some sort of sickness. She would do this the as soon as they returned for their latest adventure, he never returned.<p>The few members of the Death Knights that survived told the tale of a fierce Orcish warlord who refereed to himself as Blandar. They told the tale of the warlord's elite troops slaughtering the party, and the powerful Shade was overwhelmed with their numbers. One of the other members grabbed the magnificent dagger of the fallen shade during his retreat. The only sign of the talented Nite was a glimpse of a dark figure flanking the orcs during the parties' tactical pullback. When they returned and related the tale to Korri, the elf was crushed. She was given The Shadow Dagger as a reminder of Shade, and just a few days later she gave birth to a son.<p>She decided to name her son after the only thing she had left of her beloved. Dagger was the only thing the female elf had left in the world and she decided she would not lose him the way she lost his father. With the aid of the temple she trained the young Dagger in the art of healing. She also took him to the academy the way they had done with Nite. The young Dagger was proficient enough with magic but he was a brilliant strategist and a born leader. His stealth and grace rivaled that of both his mother and father, but his mind was his greatest asset. His interests were with anything that could be taught to him. He was fascinated with the tales of his mothers' elven tribe, and was enthralled about his father and sister. Eventually he had exhausted the knowledge of his trainers so his mother urged him to seek a larger city with more trainers.<p>Korri decided to stay behind always clutching to the hope that her daughter Nite was still alive. She wrapped The Shadow Dagger into her sons travel pack and sent him with a party of adventurers traveling to a city aptly named Fortress. There Dagger could learn the ways of the leader and the art of warrior and cleric. On the way to the great city the small party slowed and a slight murmur was heard amongst the fighters of the group. Suddenly there was a sound of scraping steel, and the area erupted in a gruesome battle. The party had no chance. Being only 10 summers old Dagger attempted to escape. He threw his pack on his shoulders and began to retreat. Suddenly there were short bolts covering the sky, then all went dark.<p>When he awoke he thought he heard the voice of his mother when she would teach him her elven tongue. The room had a musty smell and a hazy sight. He was certain the haze was because of his aching head. He could feel a bandage around his shoulder, and a pain pulsing from one of his legs. Suddenly he felt a warm touch on his leg and the pain subsided. Finally someone spoke directly to him. It was in an elven tongue so he had to concentrate to make out the words. They spoke fast but he could tell they were caring words and not angry ones. When he could see clearly he saw several figures that resembled his mother.....elves. Two figures looked different than the rest. When he looked at them, they acknowledged him with a nod. The first was a noble male elf, who was carrying his pack, and The Shadow Dagger was in his hand. Obviously the elf wanted information concerning the weapon. Then the second figure spoke.<p>She was taller than the rest with bright blond hair. She spoke in flawless common speech. The tall elf ask him where he acquired the weapon, he related a tale of his father's death and how his mother must have given him the weapon. With that the elves left. When he was able to move again the elves let him walk freely amongst their tree top village. They instructed him to go to their great magician's household.<p>When he arrived he saw the magician polishing the dagger. The magician could speak in broken common, but easily enough to understand. The elf told the story of a great Drow wizard that created weapons for the drow to use in their raids on the surface. This weapon was mysterious but the wizard was sure the weapon had intelligence bestowed upon it. The intelligence was of a chaotic sort, but was not strong enough to overcome a person if the owner was aware it was there. The rest of the powers of the weapon were unknown to the wizard.<p>Dagger lived with the elves and practiced their style of fighting. He used a sword and The Shadow Dagger similar to they way his father fought. He wore a suit of elven chain mail, and was taught the ways of the forest, and the advantages of a sneak attack. When he felt he was ready he accompanied the elves to battle the growing population of orcs. They had heard the orcs were preparing for war, but the elves were sure they didn't know the location of their home. On one of their patrols they noticed smoke in the distance. The elves went to investigate and found the town of Farreach destroyed. At the same instance the party realized what had happened they were engaged into battle. The small patrol was outnumbered 5:1 but they still attempt to fight back the orcish war party. Dagger fought back to back with the leader of the party. He fought hard not to let the experienced warrior down. Suddenly he felt the warm feeling of blood on his back. Dagger managed a glance back just to see the elf slump to the ground. Fearing death Dagger fought to bring as many orcs with him as he could. It was then a familiar sight filled the air.<p>The arrows (if you could call the small bolts that) flew fast and true throughout the sky. One orc after another fell, and with the numbers slowing going his way Dagger managed to gain an upper hand. There were a few orcs that wore heavy armor and the bolts wouldn't faze them. As soon as the bolts stopped flying a figure dropped from a nearby tree. Quickly the orcs were finished off. The dark figure easily dispatched them with a pair of shining short swords.<p>After the battle the shadowy figure finished of the sleeping orcs, and introduced herself as a half-elf assassin, friend of the tribe that trained Dagger, and referred to by those who were lucky enough to have met her and keep their life as Nite.<p>As brother and sister the two now travel as a pair. Nite taught the still young Dagger the ways of her style, which he incorporated with his own. Although few ever see Nite they know Dagger never travels far from her site. The charismatic Dagger now travels with a group calling them selves the Shadow Warriors. They seek to explore and tame new lands that are just being discovered. Even though no one else in the group has seen Nite they sometimes experience a suddenly support of arrows or the sudden death of a enemy. Dagger and Nite sometimes break from the rest of the group but always return for even this pair needs the support of a strong group.
<p><p>
		
